1. Obtain the data: Get the Dogs vs Cats dataset¶

In [3]:
import os, shutil, pathlib

original_dir = pathlib.Path("../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats/train")
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(dir)
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / fname,
                            dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=0, end_index=1000)
make_subset("validation", start_index=1000, end_index=1500)
make_subset("test", start_index=1500, end_index=2500)

In [20]:
for data_batch, labels_batch in train_dataset.take(1):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(20, 5))

    class_0_indices = tf.where(labels_batch == 0)
    class_0_indices = class_0_indices.numpy().flatten()
    for i, color in enumerate(['Red', 'Green', 'Blue']):
        if len(class_0_indices) > 0:
            first_class_0_image = data_batch[class_0_indices[0]].numpy()
            pixels = first_class_0_image[:, :, i].flatten()
            axes[0, i].hist(pixels, bins=50, color=color.lower(), edgecolor='black')
            axes[0, i].set_title(f'Pixel Value Distribution - {color} Channel for 0')
            axes[0, i].set_xlabel(f'{color} Pixel Value')
            axes[0, i].set_ylabel('Count')
        else:
            axes[0, i].set_title(f'No images for class 0')

    class_1_indices = tf.where(labels_batch == 1)
    class_1_indices = class_1_indices.numpy().flatten()
    for i, color in enumerate(['Red', 'Green', 'Blue']):
        if len(class_1_indices) > 0:
            first_class_1_image = data_batch[class_1_indices[0]].numpy()
            pixels = first_class_1_image[:, :, i].flatten()
            axes[1, i].hist(pixels, bins=50, color=color.lower(), edgecolor='black')
            axes[1, i].set_title(f'Pixel Value Distribution - {color} Channel for 1')
            axes[1, i].set_xlabel(f'{color} Pixel Value')
            axes[1, i].set_ylabel('Count')
        else:
            axes[1, i].set_title(f'No images for class 1')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

The histograms show the distribution of pixel values across the Red, Green, and Blue channels for two classes ('0' and '1').

  • Both classes have distributions across all three channels that suggest a decent variety of pixel intensity.
  • The distribution shapes for class '0' and '1' look similar across all three channels, indicating no significant color intensity difference between the classes based on these histograms alone. This similarity could suggest that color may not be the distinguishing feature between these two classes.

Modeling¶

3. Train two networks¶

1) Define a Neural Network of your choice¶

In [21]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
In [22]:
model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer="rmsprop",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

Training and Validation Accuracy:

  • the training accuracy improves consistently as training progresses, which is a good sign that the model is learning from the data.
  • However, the validation accuracy remains relatively flat and even decreases slightly over time. This indicates that the model is overfitting to the training data.

Training and Validation Loss:

  • The training loss decreases over time, which indicates learning. It's not perfectly smooth, suggesting some volatility in the training process, but the overall trend is downward.
  • The validation loss, however, increases sharply towards the end of the training. It indicates overfitting, where the model learns patterns specific to the training data, which do not generalize to the validation data.

2) Fine-Tune VGG16(pre-trained on imagenet). Make sure to use validation to test for over-fitting. Plot the appropriate graph¶

download

In [17]:
conv_base = keras.applications.vgg16.VGG16(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(180, 180, 3))

Define the model

In [20]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(inputs)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(256)(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model2 = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

Freezing all layers until the fourth from the last

In [21]:
conv_base.trainable = True
for layer in conv_base.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False

Fine-tuning the model

In [23]:
model2.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer=keras.optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=1e-5),
              metrics=["accuracy"])

callbacks2 = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="./models/fine_tuning.keras",

        monitor="val_loss")
]
history2 = model2.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=30,

    callbacks=callbacks2)

Training and Validation Accuracy:

  • Both training and validation accuracy are high, with training accuracy starting off slightly lower in the initial epochs but then consistently remaining above 95%.

Training and Validation Loss:

  • The training loss drops sharply after the first few epochs and then continues to decrease gradually, settling into a stable pattern.
  • The validation loss mirrors the training loss, which is a good sign. It stays consistent with the training loss, with no significant spikes or divergences that would suggest overfitting.

CNN

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.68      0.79      0.73      1000

    accuracy                           0.71      2000
   macro avg       0.72      0.71      0.71      2000
weighted avg       0.72      0.71      0.71      2000

Class 0:

  • precision: out of all instances classified as class 0, 68% were actually class 0.
  • recall: out of all actual instances of class 0, the model correctly identified 79% of them.
  • f1-score: f1-score for class 0 is 73%, which is the harmonic mean of precision and recall.

Class 1:

  • Precision: Out of all instances classified as class 1, 75% were actually class 1.
  • Recall: The model correctly identified 64% of all actual instances of class 1.
  • F1-Score: The F1-score for class 1 is 0.69.

threshold = thresholds[idx-1]
In [139]:
idx = (thresholds >= threshold).argmax()
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(recalls, precisions, linewidth=2, label="Precision/Recall curve")
plt.plot([recalls[idx], recalls[idx]], [0., precisions[idx]], "k:")
plt.plot([0.0, recalls[idx]], [precisions[idx], precisions[idx]], "k:")
plt.plot([recalls[idx]], [precisions[idx]], "ko",
         label="Point at threshold")
plt.xlabel("Recall")
plt.ylabel("Precision")
plt.title("Precision-recall curve")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
  • The selected threshold (where the black dot is) seems to prioritize precision slightly over recall. The model is more conservative about labeling a positive class, opting for being correct when it does so.
  • The curve starts high and slopes downward. At the beginning (towards the left of the plot), when recall is low, the classifier is very precise. As we lower the threshold to classify more items as positive, recall increases, but precision drops because the classifier starts to include more false positives.

Conclusions¶

5. Add your conclusions¶

  1. performance:
  • the cnn model has an accuracy of 71% and the fine-tune vgg16 model has an accuracy of 96.7%, suggesting that the vgg16 model is significantly outperforming the CNN.
  • The confusion matrix and precision-recall curve for vgg16 implies better at classifying and maintaining high accuracy.
  1. model complexity:
  • cnn model have fewer parameters and thus be quicker to train, but it may not capture as complex features as vgg16 unless it's specifically well-designed for the task.
  • the vgg16 model is a deep network with multiple layers and is pre-trained on a large dataset. This can give it an advantage in feature extraction over a simpler cnn model.
  1. overfitting:
  • the cnn model overfit, it might not have the capacity to learn as detailed features as the vgg16.

In conclusion, the fine-tune vgg16 appears to be the superior model for accuracy and general performance based on the metrics provided.
